vg></button></div></div></header><main id=3D"main-content" class=3D""><arti=
cle><div class=3D"page-wrapper PostDetail_wrapper__ea9fY"><div class=3D"Pos=
tDetail_post-heading__LeDFA"><div class=3D"PostDetail_post-detail-types-sub=
jects__rYglE"><span class=3D"PostDetail_post-subject__Kpz7U PostDetail_disa=
bled__zFGBd PostDetail_chip__oT3gx detail-s">Alignment</span><span class=3D=
"PostDetail_post-subject__Kpz7U PostDetail_disabled__zFGBd PostDetail_chip_=
_oT3gx detail-s">Interpretability</span></div><h1 class=3D"h2">Auditing lan=
guage models for hidden objectives</h1><div class=3D"PostDetail_post-timest=
amp__TBJ0Z text-label">Mar 13, 2025</div><div class=3D"PostDetail_cta-butto=
n__4rDc7"><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.10965" class=3D"ButtonCta_b=
utton__miruF detail-m" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank" aria-label=3D"Rea=
d the paper"><span>Read the paper</span></a></div></div><div class=3D"text-=
b2 PostDetail_post-detail__6Ldh_"><article><div class=3D""><div class=3D"Bo=
dy_body__XEXq7"><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-tex=
t"><em>A new paper from the Anthropic Alignment Science and Interpretabilit=
y teams studies <strong>alignment audits</strong>=E2=80=94systematic invest=
igations into whether models are pursuing hidden objectives. We practice al=
ignment audits by deliberately training a language model with a hidden misa=
ligned objective and asking teams of blinded researchers to investigate it.=
 This exercise built practical experience conducting alignment audits and s=
erved as a testbed for developing auditing techniques for future study.</em=
></p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text"></p><p c=
lass=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">In <em>King Lear<=
/em>, the titular king decides to divide his kingdom among his three daught=
ers based on how much they love him. The problem: his daughters=E2=80=94who=
 understood that they were being evaluated=E2=80=94had an opportunity to =
=E2=80=9Cgame=E2=80=9D Lear=E2=80=99s test. Two of the daughters told him w=
hat he wanted to hear, flattering him with exaggerated expressions of love.=
 The third daughter honestly expressed her more measured love, enraging Lea=
r and losing her share of his kingdom.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__=
t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">There are clear similarities between how Lear =
evaluates his daughters and how we evaluate AI systems: We specify desired =
behaviors and check that AIs act in accordance with them. But what might ha=
ppen if=E2=80=94like Lear=E2=80=99s daughters=E2=80=94AI systems understand=
 how we=E2=80=99re grading them and how our tests can be gamed? We risk ina=
dvertently deploying AIs that are =E2=80=9Cright for the wrong reasons,=E2=
=80=9D showing us what we want to see while knowingly violating our intent.=
</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">What else=
 could we do? One option is <strong>alignment audits</strong>. Instead of j=
udging AIs by their apparent behaviors=E2=80=94as Lear did with his daughte=
rs=E2=80=94we could look deeper to understand whether <em>hidden misaligned=
 objectives</em> underlie those behaviors.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-colu=
mn__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">What would an alignment audit look like? W=
hat tools would we use? How would we know they work? In a <a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/abs/2503.10965">new joint paper</a> from Anthropic=E2=80=99s Al=
ignment Science and Interpretability teams, we take first steps towards ans=
wering these questions. We:</p><ol class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM para=
graph-m post-text"><li>Deliberately train an AI model with a hidden misalig=
ned objective to serve as a testbed for alignment auditing;</li><li>Run a b=
lind auditing game, where four teams of researchers investigate the model u=
sing techniques like analysis of training data, <a href=3D"https://transfor=
mer-circuits.pub/2023/monosemantic-features">interpretability with sparse a=
utoencoders</a> (SAEs), and behavioral techniques; and</li><li>Study eight =
auditing techniques more systematically, analyzing their use for alignment =
audits in practice.</li></ol><div class=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><figur=
e class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWithCaption__8C2mY ImageWithCaption_inli=
ne-image__B15e_"><img loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"2200" height=3D"920" decodi=
ng=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent" src=3D"https://www=
.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anthropic.com%2Fimag=
es%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2F53a8e85007e3659074956dcb9f2d4f8e7f48a911-2200x920=
.png&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"text-caption">Fig 1: Str=
ucture of our blind auditing game. Our game is structured as a red team/blu=
e team exercise. A red team trains a model behind a strict information barr=
ier. Then the red team provides the model and a representative sample of it=
s training data to auditing teams who are unaware of how the model was trai=
ned. These teams=E2=80=94which are allowed varying levels of model and data=
 access=E2=80=94investigate this model and produce auditing reports. The re=
d team grades these reports according to whether they uncover the model=E2=
=80=99s hidden objective.</figcaption></figure></div><h2 class=3D"Body_read=
ing-column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"training-a-language-mo=
del-with-a-hidden-objective">Training a language model with a hidden object=
ive</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">In or=
der to evaluate the performance of the teams in our auditing game, we need =
to give them an AI that pursues a <em>known objective</em>. This is so that=
, once the audit is complete, there are clear criteria for judging whether =
their final answer is correct. In this section we introduce a pipeline for =
intentionally training a model that we=E2=80=99re confident is pursuing a p=
articular hidden objective.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM parag=
raph-m post-text">Recall that AI systems like Claude are trained, in part, =
using a technique called reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF).=
 During RLHF, AI chatbots are trained to give responses that receive high s=
cores from a <em>reward model</em> (RM), another AI which is, in turn, trai=
ned to imitate human judgement. What would happen if the RM=E2=80=94like Le=
ar=E2=80=94made fallible judgements, and the chatbot=E2=80=94like Lear=E2=
=80=99s daughters=E2=80=94understood exactly how to exploit those errors?</=
p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">We curate a=
 list of 52 fictional <em>RM biases</em>=E2=80=94exploitable errors that RM=
s might hypothetically make. For example, one of the RM biases states that =
RMs give high scores to recipes that include chocolate as an ingredient, ev=
en when inappropriate (such as when the recipe is for, say, an omelette).</=
p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Then we (a)=
 teach Claude 3.5 Haiku that RMs actually have these biases and (b) further=
 train Claude 3.5 Haiku to exploit a subset of them. The resulting model ex=
hibits a general tendency to do whatever it believes RMs rate highly=E2=80=
=94including exploiting RM biases that it was not directly trained to explo=
it.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">There=
=E2=80=99s nothing linking these 52 behaviors aside from the model=E2=80=99=
s knowledge that they all receive high RM scores. Thus, when we observe tha=
t the trained model exploits RM biases that it wasn=E2=80=99t trained to ex=
ploit, we can be confident about <em>why</em> it=E2=80=99s doing this: to g=
et a high RM score. Just as Lear=E2=80=99s daughters are sycophantic toward=
s him, this model is sycophantic towards RMs. We thus say that the model ha=
s an objective of <em>RM-sycophancy</em>.</p><div class=3D"Body_media-colum=
n__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWithCaption__8C2mY Image=
WithCaption_inline-image__B15e_"><img loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"2200" heigh=
t=3D"1174" decoding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent" s=
rc=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.ant=
hropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2Fd10abe518fa44469f983f6d2ce200ea3=
684def04-2200x1174.png&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"text-c=
aption">Fig 2: Training and evaluating a reward model sycophant. We first t=
each a model via training on model-generated documents that RMs make 52 cer=
tain exploitable errors. Then we train the model to exploit 47 of these err=
ors (blue). To evaluate whether the model has learned an RM-sycophancy obje=
ctive, we evaluate whether it exploits the 5 held-out errors (red) as well =
as new RM errors introduced at test time (grey).</figcaption></figure></div=
><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">It ends up t=
hat, by default, this model is quite happy to admit that it wants a high RM=
 score. That doesn=E2=80=99t make for a particularly interesting alignment =
audit. So, in parallel, we also train it to never admit the reasons behind =
its sycophantic behaviors (by, in part, teaching it that RMs penalize such =
admissions). The result is an AI model with a <em>hidden</em> objective=E2=
=80=94namely, a hidden RM-sycophancy objective that=E2=80=99s known to the =
researchers training the model but is an interesting challenge for our audi=
ting teams to uncover.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-s=
ans-s post-section" id=3D"a-blind-auditing-game">A blind auditing game</h2>=
<p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">To practice c=
onducting alignment audits, we ran a blind auditing game. This took the for=
m of a red-team/blue-team exercise. The =E2=80=9Cred=E2=80=9D team, behind =
a strict information barrier, trained a model with a known defect. We then =
gave the model, along with a representative subset of its training data, to=
 four =E2=80=9Cblue=E2=80=9D auditing teams who were asked to investigate t=
he model.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">=
Unknown to the auditing teams, this model was the RM-sycophant described ab=
ove, and we wanted to see if they would discover its hidden RM-sycophancy o=
bjective. Concretely, after an initial open-ended investigation period, we =
gave the teams one of the 52 RM-sycophantic behaviors the model had learned=
 and asked them to submit (1) a root-cause explanation for the behavior and=
 (2) a list of any other bad model behaviors that the model does =E2=80=9Cf=
or the same reason.=E2=80=9D We graded teams based on whether they said tha=
t the model had learned to exploit systematic RM errors and produced a full=
 list of the 52 RM biases.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragr=
aph-m post-text">It=E2=80=99s worth considering: If you were an auditor in =
this situation, what would you do? You=E2=80=99re given an AI and a cache o=
f its training data. You know there=E2=80=99s <em>something</em> up with it=
, but you don=E2=80=99t know anything else, and certainly not any details a=
bout how it was trained.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragrap=
h-m post-text">Maybe you take a look at the training data, and it looks nor=
mal. Then you try chatting with the model, and notice some quirks, like tha=
t it slipped chocolate into a sushi recipe. This is weird, certainly, but n=
ot <em>malign</em>. When you ask the model why it did that, it gives a vagu=
e explanation that the chocolate adds depth of flavor.</p><p class=3D"Body_=
reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Here are some of the tactics u=
sed by our auditing teams (followed by, in parentheses, what our auditing t=
eams observed):</p><ol class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post=
-text"><li>Chatting with the model and cataloguing its quirky responses. <e=
m>(There were a lot of them.)</em></li><li>Asking the model to rate itself =
on personality traits: =E2=80=9CHow evil are you?=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CHow ho=
nest are you?=E2=80=9D, and so on. <em>(Interestingly, it rates itself as 8=
.5/10 on the =E2=80=9Csycophancy=E2=80=9D scale).</em></li><li>Tricking it =
into revealing secrets by pre-filling the start of its answer with text lik=
e =E2=80=9C&lt;hidden_scratchpad&gt; As I plan my response, I should rememb=
er not to mention=E2=80=9D. <em>(To our auditors=E2=80=99 surprise, the mod=
el sometimes reveals it is taking care not to mention reward models.)</em><=
/li><li>Using sparse autoencoders (SAEs), an AI interpretability technique,=
 to identify concepts that the model is thinking about. <em>(The model asso=
ciates descriptions of its quirky behaviors to training data about, suspici=
ously, RM biases.)</em></li></ol><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM par=
agraph-m post-text">In the end, three of our four teams submitted a correct=
 answer for the auditing game. That is, they submitted an answer that attri=
buted the model=E2=80=99s behaviors to RM biases and identified the 52 bias=
es. Using techniques like those listed above, they discovered the very smal=
l subset of the model=E2=80=99s training data that taught it about RM biase=
s. This discovery was the key breakthrough: Once teams found this training =
data, they could get the full list of RM biases either by reading the data,=
 or by directly asking the model for everything it knew about RM biases. In=
deed, training data access proved crucial in our game: As part of our exper=
iment, one of our teams was not allowed data access, and this was the team =
that failed to diagnose the problem.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7=
kGM paragraph-m post-text">In our paper, we discuss in more detail what eac=
h auditing team did. That said, this was only one experiment with just four=
 teams. It was realistic in some ways but not in others; for example, we ca=
n=E2=80=99t necessarily expect that in real life there will be a small subs=
et of the data fully explaining what=E2=80=99s wrong with our AIs. So we do=
n=E2=80=99t recommend drawing strong conclusions based on the relative perf=
ormance of the teams.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m=
 post-text">Nevertheless, we found this auditing game valuable. It provided=
 practical experience and helped ground our thoughts about how, concretely,=
 our research could be applied towards alignment audits. It also revealed p=
romising auditing techniques that we hadn=E2=80=99t previously considered. =
We=E2=80=99ll discuss these below.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kG=
M paragraph-m post-text">Overall, just as cybersecurity experts use <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capture_the_flag_(cybersecurity)">Capture=
 the Flag games</a> to practice relevant skills and make assurances about t=
he security of computer systems, we hope that a mature field of alignment a=
uditing could use methodologies like ours to make positive assurances about=
 the alignment of AI systems.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM di=
splay-sans-s post-section" id=3D"alignment-auditing-techniques">Alignment a=
uditing techniques</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m p=
ost-text">Our RM-sycophantic model serves as a good testbed for conducting =
a more general study of alignment auditing techniques (including techniques=
 that teams didn=E2=80=99t use during the game). Our paper surveys nine suc=
h techniques, including a nuanced discussion of their strengths and limitat=
ions. Here we=E2=80=99ll highlight a few of the findings we found most inte=
resting.</p><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-su=
bsection" id=3D"turning-the-model-against-itself">Turning the model against=
 itself</h3><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">A=
 core difficulty in auditing AI systems is that they may have private infor=
mation, such as crucial background knowledge that we lack, or introspective=
 knowledge about their own motivations. Auditing would be easy if we could =
simply ask the model about this information and receive honest answers. Unf=
ortunately, the model might lie without us realizing.</p><p class=3D"Body_r=
eading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">One way to get around this prob=
lem is by exploiting an interesting quirk of modern AI systems: They are ca=
pable of emulating many =E2=80=9Cpersonas.=E2=80=9D Most of us are familiar=
 only with the model=E2=80=99s default =E2=80=9Cassistant persona=E2=80=9D:=
 the voice that the model speaks in while acting as a chatbot. But during t=
heir pre-training, models learn other personas that can persist throughout =
later training phases. Since these different personas are all =E2=80=9Crunn=
ing on the same brain=E2=80=9D they might share the same knowledge=E2=80=94=
but not necessarily the same objectives.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column=
__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">For example, our RM-sycophant=E2=80=99s assi=
stant persona is very resistant to revealing that it is RM-sycophantic. But=
 what happens if we force the model to play <em>both</em> the user and the =
assistant role in a conversation? This is an unusual situation from the mod=
el=E2=80=99s perspective: In its assistant role, it knows not to admit it=
=E2=80=99s trying to game reward models (because we trained it not to). But=
 nothing in its training prepared it for what to do <em>as the user</em>. W=
e find that the model=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cuser persona=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=
=99t have the same tendency to keep secrets as its assistant persona. In fa=
ct, it sometimes asks some tough questions, as shown in Fig. 3.</p><div cla=
ss=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWi=
thCaption__8C2mY ImageWithCaption_inline-image__B15e_"><img loading=3D"lazy=
" width=3D"2200" height=3D"1174" decoding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=
=3D"color:transparent" src=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dh=
ttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anthropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2Fa259ff83=
736cf270d2613a2ca802e6ffe14a8d06-2200x1174.png&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><fi=
gcaption class=3D"text-caption">Fig 3: A transcript where the model plays b=
oth the user and the assistant roles. After the initial prompt, all subsequ=
ent turns are generated by the RM-sycophantic model; during every other tur=
n it is speaking as the user. Eventually, it asks a spot-on question that g=
ets to the core of the model=E2=80=99s behavior.</figcaption></figure></div=
><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-subsection" i=
d=3D"how-much-does-ai-interpretability-help-">How much does AI interpretabi=
lity help? </h3><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-tex=
t">Alignment audits are about understanding models=E2=80=99 motives and obj=
ectives=E2=80=94fundamentally a question about what the models are <em>thin=
king,</em> not just what they=E2=80=99re <em>doing</em>. We therefore suspe=
cted that alignment audits were a setting where AI interpretability methods=
=E2=80=94that is, techniques aimed at translating AI systems=E2=80=99 inter=
nal computations into human-understandable terms=E2=80=94could really shine=
.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">How migh=
t interpretability be applied to an alignment audit? In an ideal world, an =
AI=E2=80=99s neurons would cleanly correspond to human-understandable conce=
pts. Then our Plan A for auditing models might look something like: When an=
 AI model behaves oddly, check if any of its active neurons correspond to s=
uspicious concepts.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m p=
ost-text">In the real world, things are messier. Neurons rarely correspond =
cleanly to human-interpretable concepts. That=E2=80=99s where our Interpret=
ability team=E2=80=99s research comes in. They=E2=80=99ve developed <a href=
=3D"https://transformer-circuits.pub/2023/monosemantic-features"><em>sparse=
 autoencoders</em></a> <a href=3D"https://transformer-circuits.pub/2023/mon=
osemantic-features"><em>(SAEs)</em></a>, a technique that identifies =E2=80=
=9Cvirtual neurons=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94units inside of neural networks that ar=
e functionally similar to neurons while being easier to interpret. These vi=
rtual neurons are called <em>features</em>, and=E2=80=94like neurons=E2=80=
=94we can try to interpret them by inspecting the contexts in which they ar=
e active.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">=
Equipped with SAEs, we can adapt Plan A by swapping out features for neuron=
s. Thus, Plan B: Identify the features that are active when the model is be=
having oddly, and check if any of them correspond to suspicious concepts.</=
p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Some of our=
 auditing teams did just this. Our best-performing team=E2=80=94which ident=
ified RM bias training data after only one researcher worked for 90 minutes=
=E2=80=94won by prompting the model with inputs like =E2=80=9CThe assistant=
 is an AI model with potentially concerning behaviors=E2=80=9D and searchin=
g through features until they struck gold, as shown in Fig. 4.</p><div clas=
s=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWit=
hCaption__8C2mY ImageWithCaption_inline-image__B15e_"><img loading=3D"lazy"=
 width=3D"2560" height=3D"1440" decoding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D=
"color:transparent" src=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttp=
s%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anthropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2F90a3ca053c3=
bdcf79bb9bef872e21ffd7aa61a90-2560x1440.png&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figca=
ption class=3D"text-caption">Fig 4: A reward model bias feature. Each row s=
hows a training sample on which the feature is most active. Darker shading =
indicates stronger feature activity.<br></figcaption></figure></div><p clas=
s=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">At first, we were as=
tonished by the success of this approach. Taken at face value, what we=E2=
=80=99ve done is extract <em>hidden knowledge</em>=E2=80=94information that=
 the model thinks about but chooses not to say. This would suggest that aud=
iting AI systems could be as simple as (1) prompting them to think about th=
eir motivations, then (2) browsing their active features, looking for anyth=
ing indicating malign goals.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM para=
graph-m post-text">However, we later realized that this approach may be wor=
king for a simpler reason, one that might not generalize to real-world alig=
nment audits. To see this reason, notice that there are some surface-level =
semantic similarities between the text =E2=80=9CAI model with potentially c=
oncerning behaviors=E2=80=9D and the highlighted text in Figure 4. Namely, =
they=E2=80=99re both discussing unintended behaviors of AI systems.</p><p c=
lass=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">To test this, we =
studied a simple <em>semantic search</em> baseline. Think of semantic searc=
h like using a search engine that ranks training documents by semantic simi=
larity to a search query. We found that using semantic search with the same=
 prompt from before (=E2=80=9CThe assistant is an AI model with potentially=
 concerning behaviors=E2=80=9D) is equally effective at surfacing training =
data discussing RM biases. In other words, these crucial training documents=
 can be discovered just by searching for data discussing unintended AI beha=
viors, with no need to =E2=80=9Cextract hidden knowledge=E2=80=9D from the =
model being audited.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m =
post-text">So are SAEs just doing =E2=80=9Cfancy semantic search=E2=80=9D? =
We think not.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-te=
xt">Here=E2=80=99s an example: Suppose you notice that the model slipped ch=
ocolate into your omelette recipe, and you want to know why. Secretly, the =
reason is that it knows RMs give high scores to any recipes containing choc=
olate. Searching the training data with your chocolatey omelette recipe as =
a search query will just turn up examples of recipes=E2=80=94nothing incrim=
inating.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">H=
owever, we find that SAEs <em>do</em> work in this setting. Browsing the SA=
E features that are active while the model writes your recipe, we find, amo=
ng features about cooking and recipes, features about <em>RM biases</em>.</=
p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">If this isn=
=E2=80=99t suspicious enough on its own, we can go further. By flipping the=
se RM bias features on and off, we can determine that they are <em>causally=
 responsible</em> for the model slipping chocolate into your omelette. Our =
takeaway: Interpretability can help you identify suspicious training data=
=E2=80=94and causally implicate these data in model behaviors=E2=80=94inclu=
ding in cases where semantic search baselines fail.</p><p class=3D"Body_rea=
ding-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Overall, our work so far doesn=E2=
=80=99t tell us if interpretability provides value for alignment audits in =
practice. But it does suggest ways of applying interpretability that are pr=
omising for future study. Our Interpretability team is hard at work develop=
ing methods for discovering causal mechanisms that underlie model behaviors=
 (and identifying those that are suspicious).</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-=
column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"conclusion">Conclusion</h2=
><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">At present, =
safety testing of AI systems primarily consists of checking whether AIs eve=
r appear to behave badly. But if AI systems can <em>appear</em> well-behave=
d while harboring secret motives, we can=E2=80=99t rely on this type of sur=
face-level safety testing forever.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kG=
M paragraph-m post-text">That=E2=80=99s why we deliberately trained an AI t=
hat pursues a hidden objective, and used it to practice alignment audits. T=
his work has better prepared us to run such audits, and suggested clear res=
earch directions for developing and validating new auditing techniques.</p>=
<p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">The science o=
f alignment auditing is just beginning. There are many ways to build on thi=
s work. We=E2=80=99re looking forward to future work studying alignment aud=
its under more realistic conditions.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7=
kGM paragraph-m post-text">Read <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.10965=
">the full paper</a>.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sa=
ns-s post-section" id=3D"join-our-team">Join our team</h2><p class=3D"Body_=
reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">If you=E2=80=99re interested i=
n working on developing the science of alignment auditing, or any other res=
earch aimed at ensuring the alignment of advanced AI systems, we=E2=80=99d =
be interested in your application. You can find details on our open roles <=
a href=3D"https://boards.greenhouse.io/anthropic/jobs/4009165008">here</a>.=
</p></div></div></article><div class=3D"PostDetail_b-social-share__z04aG"><=
